data.value:
A quadratic is a trinomial that can be expressed as the product of a two binomials. By splitting the equation into two binomials the roots, or solutions of the equation are easily computable. The solutions represent where the function crosses the x-axis, where y = 0. Lets take a look at an example. Say our function is in the form x^2 + bx + c where b and c are constants. For simplicity lets get a constant of 1 infront of x^2. Now, to factor this equation. The goal here is to find two numbers that when multipied, is equal to c, and the sum of those two numbers is equal to b.
x^2 + bx + c (x + d)(x + e) where d and e are the factors of c and b.
Example: x^2 -2x +1 Two numbers that multiply to +1 -> -1 and -1 Check: -1 + (-1) = -2 ->Perfect! (x - 1)(x - 1) This was a good example for a couple reasons. (x-1)(x-1) can also be re-written as (x-1)^2. What we see here is one solution, or as some say, two of the same solution, that is x=-1. The solutions to quadratic equations may or may not be distinct, and they may or may not be real. We will only focus on real roots.
